The arcade game was a major commercial success in North America, becoming the highest-grossing arcade [[1989 in video games|conversion kit of 1989]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Special Report: 1989's Best Videos and Pins |magazine=RePlay |date=January 1990 |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=44, 46 |url=https://archive.org/details/re-play-volume-14-issue-no.-4-january-1990-600DPI/RePlay%20-%20Volume%2014%2C%20Issue%20No.%204%20-%20January%201990/page/44}}</ref> In Japan, ''Game Machine'' listed ''Ninja Gaiden'' on their March 15, 1989 issue as being the second most-successful table arcade unit of the month.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25 - テーブル型TVゲーム機 (Table Videos)|magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]]|issue=352|publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press, Inc.]]|date=15 March 1989|page=21|lang=ja}}</ref>

The arcade game was well received by critics. Nick Kelly of ''[[Commodore User]]'' called it "the next generation for ''[[Double Dragon]]'' fans" with praise for the controls, background variety and two-player mode, but with some criticism towards the "slightly washed-out" graphics and "gory" continue screen.<ref name="CU">{{cite magazine |last1=Kelly |first1=Nick |title=Arcades: Shadow Warriors |magazine=[[Commodore User]] |date=19 December 1988 |issue=64 (January 1989) |publisher=[[EMAP]] |location=United Kingdom |page=103 |url=https://www.solvalou.com/arcade/reviews/275/306}}</ref> ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' called it a "slick beat 'em up" similar to ''[[Bad Dudes vs. Dragon Ninja]]'' (1988) with "smooth" graphics and "masses of action" that is "great fun" in two-player mode, despite the lack of originality.<ref name="CVG_ARC">{{cite magazine |title=Arcade Action: Shadow Warrior |magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]] |date=January 1989 |issue=88 (February 1989) |pages=102–3 |url=https://www.solvalou.com/arcade/reviews/196/306}}</ref>

Reviewing the Atari Lynx version, Robert A. Jung with ''[[IGN]]'' said the story was irrelevant and the game was a scaled down version of the arcade original. He praised the graphics but in his final verdict he wrote that "''Ninja Gaiden'' is not a bad game; it's just not a good game, either."<ref name=ignreview_lynx>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/1999/07/07/ninja-gaiden |title=The second Tecmo arcade conversion for the Atari Lynx is somewhat disappointing. |work=IGN |author=Robert A. Jung |date=6 July 1999 |access-date=18 August 2018}}</ref>
Rob Swan with ''Computer and Video Games'' said the game was exactly the same as the arcade coin-op and felt the game was a little short of superb but really addictive.<ref name=cvg_lynx>{{cite magazine |title=Lynx Lowdown |magazine=Computer Videogame Magazine |author=Rob Swan|date=August 1991 |issue=117 |page=37}}</ref>
Les Ellis gave the game a positive review in ''Raze''.<ref name=raze_lynx>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/stream/RAZE_Issue_10_1991-08_Newsfield_Publishing_GB#page/n53 |via=archive.org |title=Ninja Gaiden |magazine=Raze |author=Les Ellis |issue=10 |page=54 |date=August 1991 |access-date=18 August 2018 }}</ref>

Reviewing the Atari ST version, [[ST Review]] writes, "One of the better arcade conversions, this is a game that has stood the test of time."<ref name="STRev">{{cite web| url=https://mega.nz/file/hFcgAIQY#uZcXtTyf0TjhiB-BHxTPJDX-4feMRp7SdUdzVsNGt9w|title=SHADOW WARRIORS (Issue 2, June 1992 page 88)|website=ST Review}}</ref>

Reviewing the ZX Spectrum version, ''Your Sinclair'' praised the colorful graphics and interactive backgrounds. ''Crash'' liked the animation, but had grown tired of the genre. ''Sinclair User'' summed it up with "there isn't really a speck of originality about Shadow Warriors. Nonetheless, it will be a stiff challenge." Reviewing the Amiga and Spectrum versions, ''C+VG'' highlighted the music and sound effects.

